recordings.rmk: Unmodified recording except for cutting beginning which contained long loud blasts of train horn. Habitat: Northern White Cedars bordering on marshland. Behavior: Family of four wrens spotted recordist standing under cedar tree and began to scold, then juveniles began to approach me, flitting nervously along branches of tree as they called. Juveniles approached within a meter of me, adults not as closely. Calls alternated between whines and chatters. Temp. 47 degrees, sunny. Short narration at end of recording.

No modification; bird on old wooden fence inside old walnut tree grove. Birds flicks wings rapidly as it sings; about 4 feet off the ground, moving between fence and tree branch between singing. Possibly male? -- singing very often; sunny outside.

recordings.rmk: Habitat was cattle pastures with fragmented scrubby forest in the hills outside Bogota (on the road from La Calera to Parque Natural Nacional Chingaza).

Alarm notes of  House Wren.  The habitat, a beaver dammed steam, with small deciduous trees and pines.  The bird was seen briefly and flew.  There are two different sounds, related.  The cadence and intervals are intact.  There are two recordings joined together.  The species is a winter resident on the coast of Georgia.   Of five skilled birders, all with many years of identifying species by ear, only two would hazard a guess of House Wren.  None of us have heard this vocalization before. 

I was spishing and trilling a screech-owl call to bring birds into view.

Clipped and cleaned example of female house wren song. Background noise filtered out. Female was clearly visible and identified with using unique leg bands by recordist sitting quietly 15m away. Song was given 10 sec after female playback started. Female sang prior to playback, during playback, and after playback. Female sang 3 different song types (for an example of another song type from this female see XC263719). Male was also vocalizing in response to playback. Female was at least 4 years old. Recorded on the day of the female's 2nd egg. Weather sunny and around 65.

Song type: "male-intro song"

Clipped and cleaned example of female house wren song.  Background noise filtered out.  Female was clearly visible and identified using unique leg band colors by recordist sitting quietly 15m away. Song was given after ~3.5 min of female house wren playback.  Female sang multiple times during and after playback using a song with a similar form.  Prior to this song, female flipped her tail up and down.  Male was also present and vocalizing.  Recorded on the day of the female's 2nd egg.  Female was at least 3 years old.  Weather was partly cloudy and in the 60s.

Song type: "squeaky song"

Clipped and cleaned example of male house wren song, mate of female in recordings XC263719 and XC290447, for comparison.  Recorded during same recording bout.  Background noise filtered out.  Pair was clearly visible and identified with using unique leg bands by recordist sitting quietly 15m away.  Song was given ~3min after female playback stopped.  Male was 3 years old.  Recorded on the day of the female's 2nd egg.  Weather sunny and around 65.

Clipped and cleaned example of female house wren song.  Background noise filtered out.  Female was clearly visible and identified with using unique leg bands by recordist sitting quietly 15m away.  Song was given ~3min after female playback stopped.  Female sang prior to playback, during playback, and after playback.  Female sang 3 different song types, but only sang this type after playback (see XC290447 for another song type).  Male was also vocalizing in response to playback.  Female was at least 4 years old.  Recorded on the day of the female's 2nd egg.  Weather sunny and around 65.

Song type: "male-like song"

Clipped and cleaned segment from XC263717, example of female house wren song.  Background noise filtered out.

Recording made after a female playback trial (~5min after).  Female and male identified with unique leg band colors by an observer several meters away.  Several copulation solicitations and successful copulations observed before recording started.  Female leaned over and fluttered during many songs in this recording.  Male and female in close proximity throughout.  Weather sunny in the 70s.  Recorded on the day of the female's 3rd egg.  Female 3 years old.
XC290436 is a recording from the same female a year earlier.

Clipped and cleaned example of female house wren song.  Background noise filtered out.  Female was clearly visible and identified with using unique leg bands by recordist standing 3m away.  Song was given ~6min after female playback stopped.  Female sang many more songs in response to playback.  Female was at least 1 year old.  Recorded on the day of the female's 2nd egg.  Weather was partly sunny in the 60s.
